<user_id>118255687420082471679</user_id><user_name>Jason Moreno<//user_name>< time>
1574545470215</time>
< rating>
4< /rating>
< Review>
Stopped in this place in between meeting clients. It caught my eye as I was driving down E 14th. I'm always down for a good Cheesesteak.

This place is nice and small, about five 4 tops. The place smells of meat and onions, not bad at all. All but one table was taken and there were people waiting for orders to go. The phone kept ring for pick up orders, so that's a good sign.

The food comes out rather quickly. The sandwich comes with hot crispy fries. They use a nice sourdough roll which was really good. I actually do prefer the Amoroso's rolls for a steak sandwich but this was good too. They also use a nice provolone cheese which I like but I think there should be a Cheez Whiz option too, I got the sandwich with mushrooms and bells.

It all went together very nicely but there was just a little something missing in flavor. It was a little bland for having that much going on.

The service was great, very friendly. Looks like a husband and wife team. The wife takes the orders at the counter and the husband cooks it all up.

I'll probably go back and give another steak sandwich a try.< /Review>

<Review>I ordered a "Lover's burger" and got something that looked more like a sandwich. It wasn't quite what I expected, but it was the best burger I've had in a long time and has changed my understanding of what defines a burger. It was big and extremely flavorful with wonderfully cooked meat plus 2 cheeses: Pastrami and American. I was left wondering how it was possible for something to be so tasty. I know this place is primarily for Cheese steaks so I'll have to come back and try one but I am definitely glad I got the burger. Also the curly fries were fantastic as expected.< /Review>< user_id>

<UserId.>102717563739209538799</UserId.><username>Edgar Ceron< /username>< time>
1406226689136</time>
<rate>3<//rate>< review>
The food is good as long as you eat it while it's hot, otherwise is not as tasty. The fries that come with the order are like eating high school fries back in the day. So, I suggest to swap it for the curly or sweet potato fries they might be a better option. I tried the Philly Delux (#5) Cheese Steak sandwich which is good but I found a few minus that took away fom being fully satisfied with food. The amont of meat in the sandwich is lacking, this is noticeable when peeling back the layer of cheese. The bread is good but I felt it was too much bread but than again, I noticed it helped soak up the oil from the meat. I have also tried to the West Coast(#2), with chicken thigh, I found a lot better tasting than expected. This place has been around a long time and I noticed they have raised their prices and expanded their menu as well. Bottom line, if u feel like philly and want to support a local business try this place.< /review>

<review>Best hoagy steak place in the east bay! Maybe best in the whole bay area! Me and my friends and family are regulars. I usually get the mushroom chicken breast with swiss cheese onions and garlic added. Its the juiciest most flavorful chicken hoagy ever! The chicken is marinated in a teriyaki marinade then grilled over an open flame then chopped on the flat top grill to give it that amazing sear. It comes with fries that are nice and crispy. You can even get nacho cheese added to the fries, or even the sandwich! Great service. Great food. < Text>
I have tasted three items so far and will review each item.

Giant Bacon Cheeseburger 11$ - The Burger was good, although at 11$ it really needs to be or else this would be a 1 star review, I will note there are other burgers and sandwiches that cost less that I will be trying at a later date. The size of the burger is certainly bigger than average, but I wouldn't describe it as giant.

Chilli Cheese Fries 8$ - Large potion of fries, The fries could use a bit more salt, but its good.

Chili Cheese Dog 9$ - This isn't really a standard chili cheese dog, it's a long hot dog, cut in half, on bread, smothered in cheese and chili, in a foam tray. It's like eating Chili with some bread and hot dog mixed in there, more than a hot dog with chili on it. Large portion and it's alright. I think it really depends on preference.

Will try more menu items at a later date.< /Text>

< review>
A word of caution...

In an effort to spare someone else the trouble I experienced, I am writing this review. I recently contacted Valencia Cadillac regarding the purchase of a vehicle. I had taken the time to customize the car to my personal tastes and didn't want any issues when it came time to finalize the sale. I also wanted to be thoroughly prepared, so I spoke with a friend who works at a financial institution. He took the time to run my credit and advise me of my options in terms of financing- credit score, interest rates and monthly payments.

Unfortunately, the transaction was anything but smooth. When the car was ready, I advised Don that I wanted to pay for the car in cash. He outright refused to sell me the car in cash stating that the dealership would make no profit and he was not willing to do that. Don said that my only option was to finance the vehicle. Despite the fact that that this wasn't ideal for me, I had already gone through the trouble of customizing the car, so I heard him out. Don told me that because I already received the GM family discount, he wasn't going to shop for rates and I had to finance through him, which I know to be absolutely false. The rate that offered was several percentage points higher than what I know I qualify for. This is unacceptable. I could postulate on the reasons why Valencia Cadillac was doing their best to take advantage of me, but I won't. Whatever the reason it is; they are wrong.

As someone who is in the market for a new car every five years, their lack professionalism and ethical business practice means they not only lose out on repeat business, but also others that I feel obligated to caution against them. Ultimately, I went to another dealer and had a much better experience. I purchased the car that I wanted at a rate that was more in line with what my research yielded. Don't make the same mistake it did - save yourself time, and choose another dealership.< /review>

< Text>
New 1 star review:
I have to retract my previous review. I brought my brand-new cadillac in for it's first scheduled maintenance at Parkway, and the service department turned out to be very untrustworthy. Let me explain my proof: A few weeks previous, I got a flat on one of my tires. It was just a nail so the tire was repaired with a rubber plug. The problem with rubber plugs is they slowly let  little air out as you drive. That is the front passenger side tire, it was down about 5 psi compared to the rest. I took my car in for the first scheduled maintenance at 7400 miles, dropped the car off to the service department. They contacted me about an hour and a half later and said it was ready for pick up. I picked up the car, they gave me the "multi-point vehicle inspection" sheet that had check marks for all points of the inspection and service. Everything was marked as "green" or checked and at specs. I got in my car, and immediately noticed that the tire pressure readout was identical to when I dropped it off, the front passenger tire was still down 5 psi. A little deductive reasoning and you realize that they did not do 2 things: check the tire pressure of all the tires and rotate the tires. I brought the car back to the service department, they tried to say they forgot to "reset" the TPMS (the Cadillac has an active TPMS that always reports the exact pressure on your dashboard for each tire, no need to reset it), I told them I did not accept that and I wanted them to properly inflate the tires AND do the rotation. They took the car back for another half hour then returned it. The tires were now all reading 35 PSI. Fast forward a couple weeks... the same front passenger tire has dropped 3 PSI. That means they never did the same rotation. Now, when someone lies like this, it makes you wonder if they also lied about anything else on that multi-point inspection. On top of that, my car is now leaking oil. I do not know the cause but I suspect strongly that the service department did not do the oil change correctly. I'm having GM tow the car now to another dealership sevice department to have them re-do the service. My advice? Steer clear of the Parkway Motors Service department!!

Previous 5 star review:
I just purchased my 2013 Cadillac SRX from Parkway, and I had the smoothest transaction ever at a car dealership. Patrick Todd was the salesman and he was the best! No-pressure, no upsell hell, just a clean and fast deal! I knew exactly what I wanted and which options, and let him know. I wanted a color that is usually not on the lot, so I had to have it built from scratch. Patrick said it would be 6-8 weeks till delivery. He ordered my Caddy and I waited for it to arrive. It arrived 1 week early, and I went in. Gave it a test drive, and said I wanted to purchase. 1 hour later and it was mine!! Hany Wahba the Finance guy made the financing go so smoothly! I have never even imagined that a deal could be done with no headache like that! I got a low rate and terms that were perfect. I was ready to get my own financing if the terms were out of line, they were not! I will recommend these guys to everyone I know! Thanks for my new SRX!!!<//Text>

1375321680692<//Date>
< rating>
1<//rating>
< text>
I brought my Toyota Avalon in to have all four brakes worked on.  I was told that there was still some brake pad left so my rotors were good. I indicated that I would like the rotors turned if needed, and the manager said he would look at them. When we picked the car up, the brakes squealed and shimmied each time we applied them.  I called and asked the manager if the rotors had been turned and he said no they hadn't. He went on to infer that the problem was my fault, maybe I had overheated them, or that it shimmied before we brought the car in, ect....he did say he could look at it FOUR days later, but if he turns the rotors and its below that number, he will not let the car leave without me buying new rotors.

I felt threatened and did not want to risk more cost or damage to my car, so I didn't bring it in.

What I did learn was, on all Toyota cars, the rotors are supposed to be turned everytime the pads are replaced.  I also learned that the number is stamped on the rotor and that they can turn it just before they hit that number, they know ahead of time how much they can take off and can adjust to that.

I paid full price of 400.00 for a brake job that reminds me each time I drive of how poorly it was done and of the poor customer service that I received.<//text>

<Review>Free parking and spacious, however the coastline is rocky and finding a sandy stretch of beach that isn't crowded can be hard. Lots of fishing spots if you can avoid the kelp. Plenty of mussels and tide pools. There are tons of birds and I even saw seals hanging out. It's a beautiful piece of coast with a trail on a bluff above. Good for tide pool exploring and looking for starfish, Wakame, Nori, Konbu, and Sea Urchins.</Review><pictures>None< /pictures><response>None< /response>< gmapID>

< review>
We came here couple of times because the different vista points on different levels we could not cover at first time. This was one of the places which really led us to wake up on Saturday early mornings. There is a widespread marshland too, which itself can take a day if you want to be amazed. I am a fond of all inland water bodies which you will find a lot here. Requesting not to skip the walk in the marshes, but if you are already in a tight plan, an hour should be good to chill out in the beach here and take photos.< /review>

<userid>103851902280572776112<//userid><name>Jen Taylor Carlson</name>< Date>
1606669266449</Date>
< rating>
5</rating>
< Text>
We randomly picked a beach south of Half Moon Bay to stop at and I'm so glad it was this one. It's huge, broad, flat and gorgeous with tons of room to play and picnic and soak in the salty air. My favorite thing, though, were the tidepools, which were alive with all kinds of ocean creatures. We saw more sea anemones than I've ever seen before, sea stars of many colors, dungeness crab, hermit crabs and just off shore a colony of harbor seals. There's also a lovely marsh across the road filled with birds, including an egret rookery. The one downside is you do have to walk a bit from the parking lot to get to the beach (they've protected an area along the side of Highway One so it's safe for pedestrians) but it could be problematic if you have mobility issues. But it was absolutely spectacular!<//Text>

< Review>
Pescadero is a hidden gem along Highway 1 between Davenport and Half-moon Bay. The beach has beautiful rolling waves for the kids to play in, hiking trails that follow Pescadero creek back a ways, and shallow areas where the creek meets the ocean for alleges to explore. Parking is usually pretty good, and the beach is large enough to never be super crowded.</Review>

<UserId.>115704305255597487086</UserId.><user_name>Carlos Bonfim<//user_name><time>1622420903088</time><Rate>3<//Rate><Text>(Translated by Google) Pescadero State Beach is along State Route 1, located 14.5 miles south of Half Moon Bay and 1.5 miles west of the town of Pescadero in San Mateo County, California.

The beach has a kilometer-long coastline with sandy coves, rocky cliffs, natural pools, fishing spots and picnic facilities.

Pescadero State Beach has two distinct beach areas that are divided by the Pescadero stream.
The northern beach is wider and sandy and the southern one is rockier.
The beach to the north eventually connects to Pomponio State Beach and San Gregorio State Beach, depending on the tide level. This park is also home to a natural wetland area.

The nature reserve is a haven for steelhead, blue heron, kite, deer, raccoon, fox, skunk, barn swallow and weasel. A common bird on the rocky coast of northern California that can also be seen here is the black oystercatcher.

The coastline in the parking areas in the center and south is protected from sea waves by offshore rocks with numerous natural pools and open sea areas. This habitat is often occupied by the Steller sea lion and the seal. These pinnipeds alternately exhale, pulling them to the rocks off the coast and returning to the water to hunt nearby.

(Original)

Sometimes the birds singing in harmony with the sound of the sea waves, creating a melodious music that captivated people, in the warm sunshine of the morning ... A beautiful new day begins!

<Rate>2<//Rate>< text>
I have a 1999 4Runner that needed new struts and shocks. I requested an overall inspection at 4WP and no problems were noted by the service other than the struts and shocks. 4 Wheel Parts has competitive prices for parts and service. However, when they were finished installing the struts and shocks, they then noted that the rear track bar bushings were worn out. They tried to sell me a new track bar for about $300, when only the bushings were bad, which are around $20, after I asked about this. I asked them to order the new bushings and I brought it back a second time to have those replaced. At that time, I noticed that a lot of grease had escaped from the front axle CV boots. They then told me that these needed to be replaced after I brought it to their attention. It seems that I am doing a better job noticing problems with my 4Runner than the professionals at 4WP. Their initial inspection should have caught these other problems so that I would not have to drag this process out and notice them on my own to do one repair at a time. Overall: not impressed.</text>

<UserId.>104056637590735815636<//UserId.><name>Paul N.<//name><time>1457188832001</time>< rating>
4</rating>
< Text>
I dined there two nights in a row, as my hotel was just across the street. The dining room is nice, not too loud, considering the amount of tables set up. Their wine selection was good, but a tad expensive for selections by the glass. I thought their spinach ravioli was the better of the two meals I had. The sauce on the ravioli was good enough to dip the bread in, after I polished off all the ravioli. The bread was warm and tasty, and came with oil and vinegar. The second night, I had their free range chicken, with a (slightly) spicy sauce. The chicken was cooked very well, and the spinach side was prepared perfectly. The potatoes that came with the dish were the only low point, as they were somewhat hard and dry. Service was attentive, but just a tiny bit on the slow side one evening. Still, the waiter was friendly. I watched him go over almost the entire menu with a table of four next to me, after they just couldn't decide what to order. He was patient, and professional.< /Text>

<UserId.>107072884164321886616</UserId.>< user_name>
Marisela C< /user_name>
< Time>
1566143021427</Time>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
My girlfriend and I went there for our 1 year anniversary because we wanted to splurge a little. Side note: And also because we're boycotting Olive Garden for supporting Trump's reelection.

First, the service was great. All of the servers were aware of our needs and were filling up our waters almost every time they walked by. Second, the dinner was absolutely DELICIOUS and SIMPLE.

My girlfriend got the gnocchi al pesto and the pesto, you can tell, is homemade and absolutely delicious with blasts of flavor. Plus the gnocchi was incredibly soft, it complemented everything so well. I received the penne with the vodka sauce without bacon because we're vegetarian and OH MY WORD, that pasta dish was made with so much jam packed flavor. The sauce was absolutely amazing. Overall these two dishes tasted incredibly authentic and the portions were absolutely perfect and worth the price.

The dessert was probably the biggest surprise of the night. We opted out for the almond chocolate cake and salted caramel gelato with raspberry sauce. WOW. That's all I have to say.

You can truly tell this restaurant cares about being authentic and utilizing fresh ingredients that have incredible flavor. Will definitely be coming back for another special occasion and I highly recommend supporting this local place if you live in the Downtown San Jose area. Thank you for having us and being LGBTQ+ friendly!</Review>

<Text>It's a quite fancy restaurant with good decor and ambience. The people who work there seemed to behave as if they know of such a situation. One of the guest's meal was subpar where the parts of the spaghetti pasta were clumped and thus undercooked, causing some efforts to avoid those portions. In fact, my fish/salmon was undercooked in retrospect, which I thought at the time was intentional. Anyway, the guest was gracious enough to not cause issues with the pasta and thus found out only toward the end of the meal. We considered bringing this to the attendant but decided not to due to the earlier slow and somewhat ignorant responses and we didn't want to be late to the next event.

I am glad that I didn't get sick after eating the undercooked salmon.

Italian cuisine is one of my favorite. But, it's been less than average experience here at Il Fornaio unfortunately, especially when one considers the price...

<Name>Renae Zelmar< /Name>< review>
Came here for my parents' 30th anniversary lunch. We decided to come to the lower-reviewed San Jose location because it is closer to us and to avoid the lunch rush in Santa Clara.

I have to say that the reviews are right; service was pretty underwhelming. Our server was pretty aloof, and I never caught his name. He seemed a little annoyed about our questions about the menu. He never checked in with us after the food arrived, and we spent about half of our eating time trying to locate him to get our glasses refilled and order a drink. We felt like we were interrupting him. What for the food was also pretty long, but that doesn't usually bother us. Has some nice date night ambience, but it was kind of spoiled by the service.

The food was solid. We have had Il Fornaio catering that has blown us away, and this didn't do that. With the exception of the bruschetta, which was excellent. Petto di Pollo a la Peperonccini - essentially a grilled chicken with a spicy sauce and a kind of boring salad. Ravioli - Good! The sauce was very fresh tasting with a bit of bit. Lasag√±a - good, but very rich. Very soft and sauce-like.

So... probably worth it to go to Santa Clara for the better service. Also, parking validation for Convention Center parking only, just fyi.</review>

< Review>
The Olive bread was very good.  After that everything went downhill.  The Caesar salad was not fresh and had some brown pieces in it.  The cheese was a very salty batch that they probably got a discount on.  The pizza I order was supposed to be a Margarita Pizza and it wasn't even close.  That is a pizza that is supposed to have the three colors of the Italian flag with fresh slices of tomato, mozzarella and fresh basil.  I got a cheese pizza with two little pieces of basil.  It was salty and hands down the worst pizza I have ever had.  The average Italian would think we are idiots for eating such low quality dishes at a sky high price.

I also tried other dishes from family with me.  The salmon was the cheap Costco farm salmon and was dry.  The scallops were over cooked. Ravioli was something bad.  The lamb shank had far too much salt on it and was the best dish at the table.

What a huge disappointment the restaurant was.  They need to fire the chef.  I give it two stars, because the olive bread was good.</Review>

This is one of our most favorite restaurants with tasty meals, attentive staff, and wonderful service. For affordable eating out, enjoy their Happy Hour (4-6pm M-F) menu. <Gmap_id>0x808fccba8f6ba7d3:0xb0e4939712ce8fe1< /Gmap_id>< pictures>
None<//pictures>
<text>Excellent Italian food served by slightly harried waiters in a comfortable setting. We both chose appetizers and an entree.

My wife had a seafood sampler from the regular menu - it was exceptional with squid, tuna, scallops, and shrimp. There was a light sauce that enhanced, not overpowered, the seafood. I chose the Jota alla Triestina (borlotti bean soup) from their Friuli menu and it was an exceptional rustic soup, hearty but not rich.

We both ordered entrees from the Friuli menu. The Risotto Miramare was excellent with perfect risotto and seafood (shrimp, calamari, crab) in every bite. Balanced with peas and tomatoes it was a fantastic meal. The Gamberoni alla Busara was amazing - prawns larger than some lobster tails sauteed in paprika, garlic, brandy, capers, marinara and cream.

After our food we didn't have dessert because we were full. But I'm excited to check back for their regional specialties coming up.<//text><userid>110201923536480543982< /userid>< Time>
1548168359460< /Time>
<Resp>None< /Resp>< rate>

< review>
solid and dependable.  it‚Äôs a chain so you can basically go anywhere and get the same consistency.  plus it has been around for a long time so there‚Äôs that.

service was slow on the saturday before christmas but to be expected.  no real issues there but just be advised.

location is in the westin san jose downtown (formerly the saint claire).  parking in the area kinda sucks.  street meters max out at an hour and there is public lot across the street but at $6/hour and a $22 max it‚Äôs really not a bargain.  valet at the hotel is $15 for the first two hours with validation or $30 after that.  so factor that in.  dinging a star because of this.

food was solid if not remarkable.  parents had the tagliatelle and the linguine mare and i had the ravioli.  it‚Äôs tasty but not amazing (sorry, i got spoiled living in NYC for nine years).

worth a visit if in downtown SJ, mostly because italian here in general is very meh.  this is better than most and the decor is great.< /review>

114104347577079556242</user>
<Time>1536210634391</Time>< response>
None< /response>
<Rate>3<//Rate>< review>
We stopped in here before a show downtown. The ambiance was ok, it was around 6pm and the afternoon sun was blazing thru the windows making it pretty warm in there. I had the Tagletell bolognese and my husband had the veal. Both were good sized portions. My pasta was great. It was toothsome and perfectly al dente. The bolognese sauce was quite tasty. My husband's veal however, not so good. The sauce was lemony and bright but the veal was tough and the thin coating of flour that should have been crispy was kinda gummy. The vegetable side was a giant broccoli stem and carrot that were undercooked. The food came out fast, which was nice since we were eating pre- show, but we had to ask several times for bread (it finally came to our table after our food arrived), and our waters were never refilled. The place was fairly busy but it was a Wednesday evening at 6pm. Overall I would say this place is ok if you get pasta, but they really need to improve their service.<//review>

<user_id>110889359600338463075< /user_id><Name>Merry Yen< /Name><Time>1427654240708< /Time>< Rating>
2</Rating>
< Text>
We had dinner at Il Fornaio on Friday evening and it was a disappointing dining experience.
The restaurant wasn't very busy when we arrived, but it took the front door a while to seat us.   It then took our server a while to take our drink order, and by then we were ready to order our entrees.
Bread came warm to the table, which was one of the highlights of the meal.  My cannellini bean soup was the other highlight - rich, hearty, and flavorful.
3 out of the 4 entrees were less than expected - the meat in my bolognese sauce was very dry.  My friend got the grilled salmon (on the specials menu) and it was overcooked.  The spinach that came with it looked like it was previously frozen - it was gray and wilted.  My husband got the rigatoni with the vodka cream sauce and it was just meh.  The dishes lacked presentation and flavor, and several items were overcooked.
Service was cordial but on the slower side.
I don't think we'll return to Il Fornaio any time soon.<//Text>

< Review>
Il Fornaio is a cut above the rest. They have amazing food, great decor, and always make you feel like royalty. I love coming here every month for their Festa Regionale - where they pick a region of Italy, and their amazing chefs create a menu that reflects the flavors and culture of that region. The tasting menu is $31 and includes 3 courses. I go every month and have yet to be disappointed. I highly recommend this place!! On their regular menu, I'd suggest the Pennoni Alla Vodka or any of their Ravioli dishes.</Review>

< text>
I come to Il Fornaio a few times a year. Each time I am blown away by the service and quality of food. Kenneth Johns is an exceptional manager- the establishment is always clean- and our server Ihab did a fantastic job taking care of us.  I strongly recommend the Filet Mignon cooked rare or the Cannoli Al Forno which comes on a sizzling plate.  I've also been here for breakfast, and can say without a doubt that is the best breakfast anywhere nearby.  Take my word for it, I review many places around the world, Il Fornaio will always hold a place in my heart.</text>
